items.title: MTV Unplugged In New York (25th Anniversary)
With The Lights Out - Box Set
Nirvana Essentials
items.description: Nothing was ever quite the same after Nirvana. The band’s second album, 1991’s ‘Nevermind,’ revolutionized popular music by bringing alternative rock above ground, introducing mainstream audiences to sounds and concepts that had previously existed only in shadowy record store corners and on low-frequency college radio airwaves. ‘Nevermind’’s noisy, dissonant guitar rock, mumbled or howled surrealistic lyrics, and generally angsty punk attitudes were unlikely candidates for chart success, but the band undercut their grungy songs with enough pop melodicism to create a sound unlike anything average listeners had ever heard before, striking at the exact right moment to become an unprecedented success. Since Nirvana were rooted in an indie aesthetic but loved pop music, they fought their stardom while courting it, becoming some of the most notorious anti-rock stars in history. They consciously attempted to shed their audience with their abrasive, Steve Albini-produced third album, ‘In Utero,’ but by that point, the fate of the band and vocalist/guitarist/songwriter Kurt Cobain had been sealed. Suffering from drug addiction and manic depression, Cobain had become destructive and suicidal, though his management and label were able to hide the extent of his problems from the public until April 8, 1994, when he was found dead of a self-inflicted shotgun wound. Cobain’s death cut Nirvana’s story tragically short, but their legacy stands as one of the most influential in rock & roll history. (Photo and bio: Rovi)

items.title: Nirvana Live Essentials
items.description: One of Nirvana's most memorable live performances was its episode of MTV Unplugged, where they played everything from Nevermind cuts to songs by David Bowie and Meat Puppets. In this playlist, you'll hear tracks from that album plus music from their legendary Reading concert and 'Live at the Paramount.' (Photo: Rovi)

items.title: Nirvana: Nevermind - The Story
items.description: ‘Nevermind, It’s an Interview’ was released as a limited edition, promo only interview CD by Geffen Records in 1992. The interviews were conducted by Kurt St. Thomas whilst Music Director of WFNX in Boston, MA. Krist Novoselic and Dave Grohl's contributions were recorded on January 10th 1992 (after Nirvana’s appearance on MTV's '120 Minutes') whilst Kurt Cobain's part was recorded on January 11th 1992 (after their appearance on 'Saturday Night Live’). The CD was intended for radio airplay, and never released for sale to the public. Now, you can listen to the entire recording in a newly edited version back to back with a wide selection of classic Nirvana songs from ‘Bleach’ to ‘Nevermind’. This is 'Nevermind - the Story'. (Photo: UMG, press)

items.title: Tracks & Traces: Nirvana
items.description: Nirvana is by far one of the most beloved and influential bands of the 20th century. Among countless other achievements, the band from Aberdeen, Washington defined the grunge sound of the late '80s, spearheaded the alternative explosion of the early '90s, and, with Kurt Cobain, inhabited a frontman of iconic proportions. But even though their formula was based on the very basic principles of rock, not many, if any, has ever been able to match their incredibly well-adjusted mix of explosive power and catchy anthems, where vulnerability and anger always went hand in hand. Nirvana in general, and Cobain in particular, was always open to share the sources of their inspiration, past and present, and Nirvana never tried to hide the rich soil from where they managed to harvest new seeds. Many a band are in debt to Cobain for his including attitude, and many a music fan can thank Nirvana for getting help to explore further the sounds under their feet. This playlist aims to shed some light on the bands that shaped Nirvana – as well as those who followed in the enormous wake of their tragic and triumphant career. (Photo: Rovi)

items.title: Great Sounds From the Puget Sound: Kingsmen to Nirvana
items.description: Before Nirvana and the grunge craze hit the global mainstream in the early 1990s, Seattle and the greater Pacific Northwest was commonly regarded as a music backwoods region defined by isolation and bad weather. But in truth the Great Northwest has a long and unbroken lineage of rock ’n’ roll to its history, and today remains one of the finest and most creative hubs in the U.S. This playlist guides you through some great moments of Northwestern rock ’n’ roll pride, from the two anthems “Louie Louie” to “Smells Like Teen Spirit”, and beginning with '50s and '60s classics like The Ventures, The Wailers, The Sonics and Paul Revere and the Raiders who all shape the sounds of their time. Also including Seattle-born icon Jimi Hendrix (even though not based in town when he launched his solo career), the true midpoint of this tour centers around rock legends Heart, who fusion of metal and radio-friendly hard rock in the early 1970s bridges the gap between the glorious garage rock heyday and the '90s alternative rock boom. This is just a brief glimpse of what was going on, including influential bands in many directions; Mecca Normal (Vancouver, Riot Grrrl), D.O.A (Vancouver, hardcore), Wipers (Portland, DIY), Queenrÿche (Seattle, metal), Beat Happening (Olympia, lo-fi), Young Fresh Fellows (Seattle, power pop), U-Men (Seattle, grunge) and Melvins (Aberdeen, grunge). And since Nirvana, Alice in Chains, Pearl Jam and others permanently put the region on the map, it has continued to spew out an ever wider musical platter of great sounds from the Puget Sound – more than enough to fill up a sequel to this overview.  (Photo: Unsplash)

items.title: Remember...the 1990s
items.description: What a memorable decade! R.E.M. and U2 ascended as world stars, while grunge changed many people's perception of what could top the charts. Pop-punk (Green Day, The Offspring) and Britpop (Oasis, Blur) were born, just as hip-hop was gaining traction on the charts (Jay-Z, Eminem). Many promising hitmakers would go on to have long, healthy careers, while others would never see the 2000s. But they all belong in our collective memory of the 1990's. (Cover: The Notorious B.I.G. - Ready to Die, Bad Boy/WMG)

items.title: Nirvana: Classic Rock Influences, curated by Michael Azerrad
items.description: This playlist, curated by Michael Azerrad, whose new book is ‘The Amplified Come as You Are: The Story of Nirvana,’ surveys the surprising yet essential impact that classic rock, hard rock and metal had on the legendary grunge band. To learn more, read Azerrad’s essay ‘To Be Totally Led Zeppelin: Nirvana’s Unsung Classic Rock Roots’ on TIDAL Magazine.
